const individualSchedule = `<dl class="modal-dl">
  <dd>
    <h3>Types of PEPs</h3>

    <h4>1. Foreign PEPs</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>A natural person who has, or has had at any time, a prominent public function, or who has been elected or appointed to such a function, in a country or territory other than Guernsey.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>2. International Organisation PEPs</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>A natural person who is, or has been at any time, entrusted with a prominent function by an international organisation.
        <ul>
          <li>An international organisation is defined as an entity:
            <ol>
              <li>which was established by a formal political agreement between its member states that has the status of an international treaty;</li>
              <li>the existence of which is recognised by law in its member states; and</li>
              <li>which is not treated as a resident institutional unit of the country in which it is located.</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li>It would be appropriate to consider the UN, NATO, World Bank, and similar organisations as international organisations.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>3. Domestic PEPs</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>A natural person who has, or has had at any time, a prominent public function, or who has been elected or appointed to such a function, within Guernsey.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Definition of "Prominent"</h4>
    <p>There is not a regulatory definition of "prominent" with regards to PEPs, but the following are explicitly included:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>heads of state or heads of government;</li>
      <li>senior politicians and other important officials of political parties;</li>
      <li>senior government officials;</li>
      <li>senior members of the judiciary;</li>
      <li>senior military officers; and</li>
      <li>senior executives of state owned body corporates.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Zeta will consider the following to be "senior":</h4> 
    <table border="1" style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background-color: #1a1d3d; color: white;">
          <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left; width: 30%;">Role</th>
          <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left; width: 70%;">Includes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">heads of state or heads of government</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">All heads of state or heads of government</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">senior politicians and other important officials of political parties</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">All elected politicians of a country's highest parliamentary chamber. Elected politicians of lower chambers can be included if sufficient context justifies such inclusion.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">senior government officials</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">All ambassadors or equivalent role and all heads of the civil service or equivalent role. Other government officials can be included if sufficient context justifies such inclusion.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">senior members of the judiciary</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">All judges and equivalent roles of any level. Zeta may consider not classifying a judge or equivalent role as a PEP if sufficient evidence can be provided of the lower court status of a judge's position, but this consideration should be cautious, and the default position is that any judge or equivalent role is a PEP.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">senior military officers</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">All military officers with a NATO standard rank scale of OF-3 or higher. For countries that do not adopt the NATO standard rank scale, the rank should be best matched to the NATO standard rank scale. (<a href="https://www.nato.int/clearwriting/clearwriting_files/docs/clearwriting_styleguide.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NATO Style Guide</a>)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">senior executives of state-owned body corporates</td>
          <td style="padding: 10px;">All executive directors of state-owned enterprises are included. Non-executive directors are by default excluded but can be included if sufficient context justifies such inclusion.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4>Exclusions</h4>
    <p>Middle ranking or more junior individuals in the above categories are explicitly excluded from the definition.</p>

    <h4>Determining "Senior" Status</h4>
    <p>Where it is unclear if an individual holds, or previously held, a "senior" position, Zeta can consider the following:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The role held by the individual;</li>
      <li>The organisation, government, or other entity at which the individual is employed or affiliated; and</li>
      <li>The power, responsibilities, and influence associated with the position held by the individual.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Domestic PEPs Reference</h4>
    <p>A list of roles that qualify as Domestic PEPs is available in Appendix E of the GFSC's Handbook (<a href="https://www.gfsc.gg/sites/default/files/media/helix-file/20251028%20-%20Handbook%20on%20Countering%20Financial%20Crime%20%28AMLCFTCPF%29.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GFSC Handbook</a>).</p>

    <h4>Close Family Members and Close Associates</h4>
    <p>All close family members and close associates of PEPs are considered PEPs. The following are included in those definitions:</p>

    <h5>Close family members:</h5>
    <ul>
      <li>Spouse or partner held as equivalent to a spouse;</li>
      <li>Parent;</li>
      <li>Child;</li>
      <li>Sibling;</li>
      <li>Parent-in-law; and</li>
      <li>Grandchild.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Other family members can be considered as close if sufficient evidence justifies such inclusion.</p>

    <h5>Close associates:</h5>
    <ul>
      <li>A person who is widely known to maintain a close business relationship with such a person; or</li>
      <li>A person who is in a position to conduct substantial financial transactions on behalf such a person.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Those persons considered to be close associates could include known partners outside the family unit who would not qualify as close family members (for example, girlfriends, boyfriends and extra-marital partners), prominent members of the same political party, civil organisation, labour or employee union as the PEP, and business partners or associates, especially those that share beneficial ownership of a legal person or legal arrangement with the PEP, or who are otherwise connected (for example, through joint membership of a company board where the PEP and/or close associate is a beneficial owner). Any other persons can be considered as close associates if sufficient evidence justifies such inclusion.</p>

  </dd>
</dl>`;

